docs.abstract: Beijing plans to reorganize its financial, environmental and anti-corruption agencies as President Xi Jinping solidifies his hold on official levers.
docs.snippet: Beijing plans to reorganize its financial, environmental and anti-corruption agencies as President Xi Jinping solidifies his hold on official levers.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — The Chinese government said on Tuesday that it planned to overhaul supervision of the country’s debt-ridden financial sector, its environmental regulators and other essential government agencies in a broad move intended to further consolidate the Communist Party’s hold on official levers of power.

headline.main: China’s Communist Party Centralizes Power Over Finance and Pollution Control
headline.print_headline: China Tightens Controls Over Financial Sector

byline.original: By Keith Bradsher and Chris Buckley

docs.abstract: A weekend blizzard was still filling the mountain valley with more snow on Monday night as heads of state and C.E.O.s tried to gather for the World Economic Forum.
docs.snippet: A weekend blizzard was still filling the mountain valley with more snow on Monday night as heads of state and C.E.O.s tried to gather for the World Economic Forum.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — It may be tempting fate to try to gather 60 heads of state and hundreds of global business leaders in the dead of winter in a Swiss mountain valley. This year, the World Economic Forum’s luck seems to have run out.

headline.main: Heads of State and C.E.O.s in Davos Beware: 6 Feet of Snow in 6 Days

docs.abstract: Chinese-made goods become more valuable to Beijing as an increasing number of parts and components it once bought from the United States are made at home.

docs.lead_paragraph: SHANGHAI — China’s economy grew at a healthy pace in the first three months of this year, propelled by strong household spending and heavy government investment in infrastructure.

headline.main: China’s Economy Grows, and Its Trade Gap With the U.S. Widens
headline.print_headline: China’s Economy Grows by 6.8%, and Trade Gap With the U.S. Widens

docs.abstract: Guo Shuqing, the top banking and insurance regulator, was picked to be the central bank’s Communist Party secretary, overseeing the governor, Yi Gang.
docs.snippet: Guo Shuqing, the top banking and insurance regulator, was picked to be the central bank’s Communist Party secretary, overseeing the governor, Yi Gang.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — Less than a week after naming Yi Gang as the governor of China’s central bank, leaders in Beijing have unexpectedly put a different man above him as the Communist Party secretary at the central bank, five people familiar with the decision said on Sunday.

headline.main: China Splits Top Jobs at Central Bank, Adding Another Reformer
headline.print_headline: China Splits Top Jobs at Central Bank, Adding 2nd Reformer

docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — President Xi Jinping of China is sending his top economic policymaker to Washington on Tuesday in a bid to reduce trans-Pacific trade tensions before China’s congress convenes for its annual session.

docs.abstract: The agreement signals that the Google driverless-technology spinoff plans a rapid start for a business set to get underway later this year.
docs.snippet: The agreement signals that the Google driverless-technology spinoff plans a rapid start for a business set to get underway later this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Waymo, the driverless-technology company spun out of Google, has agreed to purchase as many as 62,000 minivans from Fiat Chrysler Automobiles for use in a ride-hailing service set to begin commercial operations later this year.

headline.main: Waymo to Buy Up to 62,000 Chrysler Minivans for Ride-Hailing Service
